<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="section-1" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Creating the First Program</title>
  
  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Startup the p5.js editor and properly log in</p></li>
      <li><p>Use the p5.js editor</p></li>
      <li><p>Run the default program</p></li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <p>
    The p5.js editor is where we will write, save, and run our JavaScript programs. We will 
    use some elements from the p5.js library to make our programs visual, which helps us to 
    <q>see</q> whether or not our program is doing what we want it to do. 
  </p>

  <p>Let's get started!</p>
  <p>Open the editor in your browser: <url href="https://editor.p5js.org/"/> or you can search for <alert>"p5js editor"</alert></p>
  <p>To enlarge any image, click once on the image. Click again to make it normal size.</p>
 
  <figure xml:id="new-editor">
    <caption>A new editor, with a code window that contains <alert>template</alert> code</caption>
    <image source="images/NewEditor.png" width="80%"/>    
  </figure>

  <p>Choose <alert>Log in</alert> in the upper-right corner.</p>
  
  <figure xml:id="login-screen">
    <caption>The log in window. Select, Login with Google - make sure that you are logged into your CA Google account.</caption>
    <image source="images/LoginScreen.png" width="40%"/>    
  </figure>

  <p>You log in so all the programs that you write can be saved under your account.</p>

  <p>Press the <alert>Play</alert> button.</p>
  
  <figure xml:id="fig-blank-canvas">
    <caption>Creates a blank canvas - the gray square on the right.</caption>
    <image source="images/NewEditorRun.png" width="80%"/>    
  </figure>

  <p>Although they are too tiny to see, the default canvas is made up of 160,000 (400x400) dots called <term>Pixels</term>. 
     We will explore pixels more in the following sections.</p>

  <p>We will ofter use <term>js</term> for JavaScript and <term>p5</term> for either the p5.js editor or library.</p>   
</section>